          <strong>About MyRecipes App</strong>
        </h3> 
        <h5 style="color:black; font-family:Times New Roman"><em><blockquote>
        Through building MyRecipes app, I was able to get hands-on-experience with setting up the development environment, the production environment, and the test environment in Rails. The development process entailed an extensive MVC setup for the following tables: chefs, ingredients, styles, likes, recipe_ingredients, recipe_styles, reviews, and recipes. Here I worked on establishing polymorphic asssociations between the aforementioned tables, nested attributes, single table inheritance, as well as setting up nested routes. I built the user authentication system from scratch, using the bcrypt gem to ensure that users' passwords are safeguarded. </br>
      </br>
        MyRecipes App was written in Ruby version '2.2.2'; the app uses AWS Storage for image upload through the configuration of AWS S3 environment keys using Carrier Wave. Users have the ability to setup their own custom gravatar since I appended the <a href="https://en.gravatar.com/">Gravatar url</a> to the chefs model. I integrated the Twitter Api, so users can sign in to Twitter through MyRecipes App. The scope of Twitter Api integration was expanded to where users can search Twitter via MyRecipes, and will be immediatedly routed to the Twitter site, yielding their search results. Other cool features of MyRecipes: users ability to like/dislike other recipes, pagination, and image upload.</br> 

